reviews_data.review_text:
Honestly, it really makes me sad to have to make this review.

My entire family are frequent visitors to  220c, we never had issues for the last couple years but a month or 2 ago we went as a family around 11am and we had the worst experience ever. The entire place was dirty, food we ordered took over 25 minutes. After ordering, 10 minutes after they came and told us they didn't have the food (sandwich), 5 minutes after that they brought our coffees out 2 ice teas, 2 hot coffee and the hot coffee was cold. When I asked the young 2 men at the front they said "that's how we make it" even though I seen the coffee with my own eyes sit for over 5 minutes behind the counter. When I asked again, they got upset and said best we can do is microwave it, I'm serious. was told manager or owner was not here but on a trip or something. We spent over $120 for this experience for 4 people. most of my friends and family began going elsewhere for similar food and have had better experience there.

Now a month or 2 later I was getting work done on my vehicle next door and decided to give it another try, maybe it was just a one time terrible experience. Upon entering, everything was clean and I was pleased until I ordered a sandwich and a hair was in it half was while I was eating. I threw my sandwich away and left, I won't be returning sadly. Friends and family mentioned having worse experiences recently as well, so unfortunately it seems 220C Banh Mi has lost its charm, quality of service, and quality of food.
reviews_data.owner_answer:
Dear Joseph,

We appreciate you sharing your feedback and are genuinely sorry to hear that you left with such an impression. We take all customer experiences seriously and always aim to provide great service, cleanliness, and quality food.

That being said, we would like to clarify a couple of points for the sake of accuracy. Our management is present daily, especially during the 11am rush, so the statement that there was no manager or owner available at that time is not correct. We believe in being hands-on with our team and customers, and we are always on-site to address any issues that arise.

We understand that no business is perfect and that mistakes can happen, but this review does not reflect the standards or daily practices we uphold at 220 °C Banh Mi and Coffee. Many of our guests have positive experiences with us, and it is disappointing that this review does not represent the full picture of who we are or the service we provide.

While we regret that your visit did not meet expectations, we remain committed to our values and to continuously improving for all of our customers.

Sincerely,
Alex and Cece
Owners/Managers, 220 °C Banh Mi and Coffee

Five stars are not enough to express how espresso 220C Banh Mi & Coffee executes.  The Vietnamese Coffee is excellent!!!

Step aside, world, because 220°C has officially perfected the art of caffeination and carb celebration! If you're in the mood for a coffee experience that makes you want to break into a happy dance, this is your spot. Their coffee is like a warm hug from your most caffeine-obsessed friend – perfectly brewed and packed with flavor.

Now, onto the banh mi sandwiches. Picture this: crispy pork that's so crunchy, it's like a piggy orchestra playing a symphony in your mouth. The veggies? Fresh and crunchy enough to make a salad jealous. And don't even get me started on the bread – it's like they found the secret to baking clouds.

But it's not just about the food; the staff here could charm the socks off a snake. They're friendly, efficient, and they actually smile like they mean it. And here's the kicker – they have an app for ordering takeout that's so easy, even your technologically-challenged grandma could use it.

So, if you're looking for a place where the coffee flows like a river of liquid gold and the banh mi are a party in your mouth, 220°C is your new happy place. Trust me, you'll leave with a belly full of goodness and a heart full of joy. Five stars and a high-five to 220°C!"

Zen Lesson Failed: A Matcha Saga

So, here I am—very pregnant, with a massive belly—deciding to treat myself to a lovely matcha and some pastries. I walk into a café and, miracle of miracles, there’s no line! I think, Wow, this is going to be quick.

I order three desserts and three matcha drinks. The barista nods, and I relax. But then… 25 minutes pass. Twenty-five minutes! Apparently, this man has taken it upon himself to train my patience in preparation for labor. I stand there, watching him like a hawk, silently willing him to hurry up.

At some point, I start wondering—did he send a group of celestial virgins to the matcha fields to hand-pick the freshest leaves just for me? Because I see no other reason for this delay.

Then, his friend walks in. And this guy, without a second thought, puts my order on hold to casually chit-chat, as if I don’t even exist! That’s when I officially lose my Zen. No more inner peace, no more joyful anticipation. Instead, I hiss through gritted teeth, “Long. VERY long.”

I am never coming back here. But I have to admit—the matcha was heavenly, and the pastries were absolute perfection. Probably infused with the fiery energy of all the burning asses of frustrated customers forced to wait 25 minutes for their tea.

Wishing you all peace and patience. Mine has officially run out. No one bothered to apologize for their attitude, even though the prices weren’t exactly cheap. I paid around $45 for my order.
reviews_data.owner_answer:
Thank you for enjoying our pastries and matcha drinks!

We appreciate all feedback, but we want to clarify a few things. Your order was prepared in the order it was received, and there were other customers ahead of you. Everything we make is fresh and to-order, which takes time (it actually took a total of 15 minutes from receiving your order, finishing previous customer orders, taking new orders, and completing yours).

As for us acknowledging another customer, it’s part of providing good service, not ignoring anyone. When you thought the order was “put on hold”, the order was still being made by Cece, who was behind “this guy”. Maybe had Cece been the one to speak to the customer, you may have interpreted it a different way. We understand that waiting can be frustrating, but rudeness toward staff is never acceptable nor appreciated. We stand by the quality of our products and we always strive to provide good service as well. Wishing you the best!

reviews_data.owner_answer: Hi Shirley! Thank you for your feedback. We can see where you’re coming from and want to share with you what’s going on. This is how we make our cappuccinos: 2oz espresso, 8oz milk. Steaming the milk will also produce 2oz of foam, which in total makes a 12oz cappuccino. If you let the foam disappear, you will be left with a drink that should be around 10oz, depending on how much foam you got. Zen Lesson Failed: A Matcha Saga

So, here I am—very pregnant, with a massive belly—deciding to treat myself to a lovely matcha and some pastries. I walk into a café and, miracle of miracles, there’s no line! I think, Wow, this is going to be quick.

I order three desserts and three matcha drinks. The barista nods, and I relax. But then… 25 minutes pass. Twenty-five minutes! Apparently, this man has taken it upon himself to train my patience in preparation for labor. I stand there, watching him like a hawk, silently willing him to hurry up.

At some point, I start wondering—did he send a group of celestial virgins to the matcha fields to hand-pick the freshest leaves just for me? Because I see no other reason for this delay.

Then, his friend walks in. And this guy, without a second thought, puts my order on hold to casually chit-chat, as if I don’t even exist! That’s when I officially lose my Zen. No more inner peace, no more joyful anticipation. Instead, I hiss through gritted teeth, “Long. VERY long.”

I am never coming back here. But I have to admit—the matcha was heavenly, and the pastries were absolute perfection. Probably infused with the fiery energy of all the burning asses of frustrated customers forced to wait 25 minutes for their tea.

Wishing you all peace and patience. Mine has officially run out. No one bothered to apologize for their attitude, even though the prices weren’t exactly cheap. I paid around $45 for my order.

reviews_data.owner_answer: Hi Shirley! Thank you for your feedback. We can see where you’re coming from and want to share with you what’s going on. This is how we make our cappuccinos: 2oz espresso, 8oz milk. Steaming the milk will also produce 2oz of foam, which in total makes a 12oz cappuccino. If you let the foam disappear, you will be left with a drink that should be around 10oz, depending on how much foam you got. If you want a drink with more steamed milk and less foam, we recommend the latte, as it will be more steamed milk and less foam for you!
